@r 2.4 signed and unsigned numbers
@s binary digit/bit: one of the two numbers in base 2,
0 or 1, that are the components of information
@t value of ith digit d: $d \cdot b^i$, where $b$ is base.
@u least significant bit: rightmost bit in MIPS word
@v most significant bit: leftmost bit in MIPS word
@w overflow: when the results of an operation are larger
than can be expressed in a register
@x sign and magnitude representation
@y two's complement
@z leading 0s positive, leading 1s negative
@10 all negative numbers have 1 in MSB
@11 sign bit
@12 loads
@13 signed load
@14 copy sign repeatedly to fill rest of register
@15 sign extension
@16 unsigned load: fill left of data with zeros
@17 32 bit word load is identical for
signed/unsigned
@18 byte loads
@19 load byte (lb)
@1a load byte unsigned
@1b useful shortcuts
@1c negate: invert 0 to 1, 1 to 0, add 1
@1d $x + \overline{x} = -1$, $x + \overline{x} + 1 = 0$,
$\overbar{x} + 1 = -x$.
@1e convert binary in n bits to number with more than n bits
@1f one's complement: notation where 10...0 most negative
and 011..1 most postive
@1g equal amount of positive/neagtives, 2 zeros pos 0..0 and
neg 1..1
@1h negative found via inverting each bit $\overline{x}$
@1i biased notation
@1j most neg 0..0, most positive 1..1
@1k 0 typically 10..0
@1l biases a number to have non-negative representation
